project-description.html.title: Project Description
project-description.html.body:
Project Description
This is a Tensor Engine (TE) sample project, including the sample code of the single operators sign and reduction and a script for generating sample data.
You can quickly develop TE operators based on this sample project.

project-path.html.title: Project Path
project-path.html.body:
Project Path
The sample path is $HOME/tools/che/ddk/ddk/sample/tvm.

 NOTE:$HOME/tools is the default installation path of the DDK.

project-import.html.title: Project Import
project-import.html.body:
Project Import

In the  New Project dialog box of Mind Studio, choose  Operator Project > Tensor Engine Project, select  Local (WebServer)  from the  Source Code From  down list box, and set  Local File Path  to  $HOME/tools/che/ddk > ddk > sample > tvm.
Click  Next. The model configuration dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Network model configuration
Set  Model File  to a model file. Select the check box of the first layer in the  Custom Layer  area.

 NOTE:You can import any model file converted by any tool so that custom operators can use its framework.  


Click  Create. A Tensor Engine project is created by importing the sample project, as shown in  Figure 2.
Figure  2  Sample TVM project
Table 1  describes the code directory structure.
Table  1  Code directory structure

Directory

Description



BatchNorm_plugin

Code directory for the custom operator plug-ins
This sample implements only operators. The implementation of the operator plug-in is not involved.


operator

Directory for storing the implementation code of an operator


proto

proto files of the built-in operators of the tool 


DataGen.py

Script for generating sample data


test_tvm_reduction.py

Implementation sample of the reduction operator


test_tvm_sign.py

Implementation sample of the sign operator

sample-data-generation.html.title: Sample Data GeneratIon
sample-data-generation.html.body:
Sample Data GeneratIon
Perform the following steps to manually execute the data generation script in the sample project on the Mind Studio server:

Go to the path of the new project.
For example, if the name of the new sample project is  tvm-pro, run the following command:
cd  /projects/tvm-pro

Run the DataGen.py script to generate sample data:
python DataGen.py
Eight data files as listed in  Table 1  are generated. The files starting with  sign are the input data and verification data for operators in  test_tvm_sign.py. The files starting with  reduction are the data for the subtraction operations. 
Table  1  Description of generated data files

Data File

Description



reduction_input_2_3_4_sum_axis_1.data

Input data file of the reduction operator in binary format


reduction_input_2_3_4_sum_axis_1.txt

Binary file of the reduction operator in .txt format for users to easily view the results


reduction_output_2_3_4_sum_axis_1.data

Output data verification file of the reduction operator in binary format, which is used to verify whether the output is correct after the operator runs


reduction_output_2_3_4_sum_axis_1.txt

Output data file of the reduction operator, which is visible to users and has the same functions as reduction_output_2_3_4_sum_axis_1.data.


sign_input_2_4_cce.data

Input data file of the sign operator in binary format 


sign_input_2_4_cce.txt

Binary file of the sign operator in .txt for users to easily view the results


sign_output_2_4_cce.data

Output data verification file of the sign operator in binary format, which is used to verify whether the output is correct after the operator runs


sign_output_2_4_cce.txt

Output data file of the sign operator, which is visible to users and has the same functions as sign_output_2_4_cce.data





The preceding data dimensions are all (2, 4), that is, in two rows and four columns.

project-compilation.html.title: Project Compilation
project-compilation.html.body:
Project Compilation
A TE operator is automatically compiled when the project is running. The following uses the sign operator in the sample project as an example.

Select the sample project and choose  Run > Edit Run Configuration...  from the menu bar. The  Run Configurations dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 1.
Figure  1  Run Configurations dialog box

Configure the of TE parameters.
The TE run configurations consist of three tab pages.
Table  1  Description of TE configuration parameters

Configuration Area

Description



Target

Specifies the information of the run target.
For an ASIC project, enter the IP address of the host.For an Atlas DK project, enter the IP address of the developer board.


Input

Describes the input and output data of the operator.
Custom Operator Name:name of a single operator. After a project is created, the name is automatically displayed.
INPUT_PARAM: description of the input data. You can add a maximum of 20 data records.Input0: first input data
File Path: input data file. Select the binary input data file built in Sample Data GeneratIon.
OUTPUT_PARAM: description of the output data. You can add a maximum of 10 records.Output0: first output data
File Path: output data file. The default file is the out0.data file relative to the output folder.Data Size: size of the output data, in bytesData Type: output data type, float16 or float32.



Verify

Provides parameters for checking whether the output of the running parameter configuration in the Run Configurations dialog box is consistent with the expected result. Parameters on this tab page are optional. If they are not set, the system does not check the correctness of output data during running.
Figure 3 shows the configuration example. The configuration items are described as follows:
EXPECT_PARAM: expected result of the user, which is used to check the output result. The number of data records must be the same as the number of output data records. A maximum of 10 data records can be entered.Expect0: first verification data
File Path: data verification file. You are not allowed to manually edit the file path.

Precision Deviation: allowed precision deviation. The value range is [0, 1). The default value is 0.2. A smaller value indicates higher precision.Statistical Discrepancy: percentage of data whose precision deviation does not meet the threshold in the entire data set. The value range is (0, 1). The default value is 0.2. A smaller value indicates higher precision.





Figure  2  Configuration example of the Input tab page
Figure  3  Configuration example of the Verify tab page

 NOTE:Tensor Engine performs data verification only after the following requirements are met: (1) The number of parameters in the  EXPECT_PARAM  area are the same as that in the  OUTPUT_PARAM  area in the  Run Configurations  dialog box. (2) No configuration option on the  Verify  tab page is left blank.  


After the configuration is complete, click  Save.

project-description-0.html.title: Project Description
project-description-0.html.body:
Project Description
The fasterrcnn_vgg16_asic sample project is compiled based on the fastrcnn(vgg16) detection network. The sample code implements the input of the BGR data to the inference module, and the output of the boxes of the detected targets and the confidence values of the classification.

project-path-1.html.title: Project Path
project-path-1.html.body:
Project Path
The sample path is $HOME/tools/che/ddk/ddk/sample/fasterrcnn_vgg16_asic.
Because the weight file of the Faster-RCNN Caffe model is large, it is not included in the product package. To run this sample, you need to download the model file and weight file of the fasterrcnn_vgg16 network and convert the network model into a model supported by Ascend 310 by referring to  Data Input.

data-input.html.title: Data Input
data-input.html.body:
Data Input

Parameter

Description



BGR test data to be classified

/test_data/data/faster_rcnn.bin in the project directory (180 x 300)


Faster-RCNN (vgg16) model

Model name: FasterRCNN-vgg16.davinci.om
Conversion method:
Place the faster_rcnn_vgg16 Caffe model file in the test_data/model_gen directory and rename the file FasterRCNN_VGG16_180x300_do.caffemodel.
Go to the test_data/model_gen directory and run the following commands:
1. su root
2. export LD_LIBRARY_PATH=/Installation directory>/tools/che/ddk/ddk/uihost/lib
3. /Installation directory>/tools/che/ddk/ddk/uihost/bin/omg  --model=./FasterRCNN_VGG16_180x300_do.prototxt --weight=./FasterRCNN_VGG16_180x300_do.caffemodel --framework=0 --aipp_conf=aipp_nv12_img.cfg --output=./FasterRCNN-vgg16.davinci  --op_name_map=./model_face.txt
FasterRCNN_VGG16_180x300_do.prototxt is the network model file, aipp_conf is the AIPP configuration file, and op_name_map is the operator mapping configuration file (specified when the DetectionOutput network is included). The three files can be obtained from the test_data/model_gen directory in the project directory.
For details about the parameters, see the Mind Studio Basic Operations.
Place the converted FasterRCNN-vgg16.davinci.om file in the test directory (the file is in the same directory as the executable my_vgg16 file).
Note: You can also convert the model by using the Mind Studio GUI. For details, see Mind Studio Basic Operations.


Graph configuration file

/test_data/config/sample.prototxt in the project directory

project-compilation-4.html.title: Project Compilation
project-compilation-4.html.body:
Project Compilation
You do not need to write  Makefile. You can compile the file on the compilation GUI provided by Mind Studio as follows:

Select the project whose project structure needs to be configured, and then choose  Build > Edit Build Configuration. The window for configuring a custom project is displayed.
Configure a custom project.
The custom configuration project consists of three tab pages:  Main, Host, and  Device.
Each .so file needs to be configured on the corresponding tab page based on the  side  value of each engine in the  sample.prototxt file.
Table 1  describes the  Main, Host, and  Device  parameters.
Table  1  Configuration description

Configuration Area

Description



Main

To generate the executable file, choose Build > Edit Build Configurations > Main. In the Files area, select all .cpp files in the host/src directory.
In the Include Path area of the Build Options dialog box, fill in the common directory /common and host directory /host.
To view the value of , right-click in the project directory on the left and choose Show References from the shortcut menu. Separate multiple directories to be included by spaces.
For example: /projects/my_vgg16/common  /projects/my_vgg16/host
After the configuration is saved, the CMakeLists.txt file is generated in the build folder under the root directory of the project.
After the compilation is successful, the executable file my_vgg16 is generated in the out folder.


Host

Add the engine that needs to run on the host and enter the engine name.
In this sample, this tab does not need to be configured.


Device

To generate the device library, choose Build > Edit Build Configurations > Device and set Engine Name to faster_rcnn_vgg16 (which is the name of the generated .so library file, and cannot be the same as other generated files). In the Files area, select all the .cpp files in the device/src directory.
In the Include Path area of the Build Options dialog box, fill in the common directory /common and device directory /device.
To view the value of , right-click in the project directory on the left and choose Show References from the shortcut menu. Separate multiple directories to be included by spaces.
For example: /projects/my_vgg16/common  /projects/my_vgg16/device
Save the configuration and a folder with the same name as the engine name is generated, which contains the CMakeLists.txt file in the build folder under the root directory of the project.
The .so file is generated in the out folder.
 NOTE: The .so file needs to be signed to avoid being tampered with. The signing method is as follows:
Call the RSA_generate_key interface of the OpenSSL tool to generate the public key pub.pem and the private key pri.pem. The recommended key length is greater than or equal to 2048 bits.Use the private key to sign the .so file using the SHA256 algorithm to generate the .so.signature file, which is stored in the same directory as the original .so file.Call the SetPublicKeyForSignatureEncryption interface to transfer the public key to HiAI Engine. For details about the APIs, see the HiAI Engine API Reference.






Which of the three tab pages is configured depends on which side the .so file of the engine needs to be used. In this sample, SrcEngine and DestEngine are configured on the  Main tab page while faster_rcnn_vgg16 is configured on the  Device tab page. The following figures show the compilation configuration examples.
Figure  1  Configuration example on the  Main  tab page
Figure  2  Configuration example on the  Device tab page
Click  Build Options  in the  Build Configurations  dialog box. A dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 3.
Figure  3  Main tab in the Build Options dialog box 
Figure  4  Device tab in the Build Options dialog box 

 NOTE:   

On the  Main tab page, set  Include Path to  /projects/my_vgg16/common  /projects/my_vgg16/host.  
On the  Device tab page, set  Include Path  to  /projects/my_vgg16/common  /projects/my_vgg16/device.  


Table 2  describes the parameters on each tab page of the  Build Options dialog box.
Table  2  Parameters in the Build Options dialog box

Parameter 

Description



Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt

This check box is selected by default.
If this check box is selected, the CMakeLists.txt file is automatically overwritten each time the configuration is saved. (If the Makefile is modified, the CMakeLists.txt file will also be overwritten.)If this check box is deselected, the CMakeLists.txt file is not automatically overwritten each time the configuration is saved.


C++ Standard

C++ standard. The options are as follows:
C++ 11C++ 98
The default setting is C++ 11.


Debug Flags

Compilation mode. The options are as follows:
DebugRelease
The default setting is Debug.


Cpp Flags

Compilation option, which is configured by users.


Link Library

Referenced link library, which can be configured by users.
Linked dynamic library, corresponding to the value of -l in the compilation command.


Lib Path

Link library path. Currently, the default path is used. You can add configuration.
Dynamic library search path, corresponding to the value of -L in the compilation command.


Include Path

Header file path. Currently, the default path is used. You can add configuration.
Header file search path, corresponding to the value of -I in the compilation command.





After the configuration is complete, click  Save  to save the project structure configuration. Click  Build  to compile the project structure.

In the  Build Options  window, if  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  is selected, the  build  window will display the generation information of CMakeLists.txt files, and the  build  folder that stores the CMakeLists.txt files is automatically generated in the root directory of the project, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  Project directory example

If  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  in the  Build Options  window is deselected:

If the  build folder does not exist in the root directory of the project or the  build folder in the root directory of the project does not contain the CMakeLists.txt  file, the  build folder containing the  CMakeLists.txt  file is automatically generated, as shown in  Figure 5.
If the  build  folder containing the CMakeLists.txt  file exists in the root directory of the project, the  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 6.
Figure  6  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt prompt
If you click  OK, the original  CMakeLists.txt file is overwritten.
If you click  Cancel, the  CMakeLists.txt  file in the current project directory is used for compilation, and no more  CMakeLists.txt file is generated.




After the project compilation is complete, the  build  window displays the result, as shown in  Figure 7.
Figure  7  Compilation output window
After the compilation is successful, the out  folder is generated in the project root directory, as shown in  Figure 8.
Figure  8  out folder after compilation
The  my_vgg16  file in the  out folder is the executable file for the host, and the  libfaster_rcnn_vgg16.so  file is the .so file for the device.

 NOTE:   

The folders and files that are not selected by the main engine, host engines, and device engines in the project are skipped during compilation.  
If a project that has not been configured is compiled in one-click mode, the  build folder that exists in the root directory of the project is directly used to compile the project if the folder contains the  CMakeLists.txt file. Otherwise, the project is compiled using the selected configuration.  
If a project is renamed, you need to change the path value of  Files  on the  Main,  Host, and  Device tab pages. If the previous configuration is run, the generator generates an invalid project with the original project name based on the path value in the original  Files.

project-description-7.html.body:
Project Description
The classify_net_asic sample project is a sample code that integrates multiple classification networks. The sample code is used to input BGR data to the inference module and output the classification confidence value, including networks such as ResNet-18, ResNet-50, ResNet-101, ResNet-152, ResNext-50, ResNext-101, vgg16, vgg19. The command for running a network is, for example,  ./classify_net resnet-18.
The following uses the ResNet-18 network as an example.

Project Compilation
Perform compilation on the compilation GUI provided by Mind Studio. In this compilation mode, you do not need to compile Makefile. The detailed procedure is as follows:

Select the project whose project structure needs to be configured, and then choose  Build > Edit Build Configuration. The window for configuring a custom project is displayed.
Configure a custom project.
The custom configuration project consists of three tab pages:  Main, Host, and  Device.
Each .so file needs to be configured on the corresponding tab page based on the  side  value of each engine in the  sample.prototxt file.
Table 1  describes the  Main, Host, and  Device  parameters.
Table  1  Configuration description

Configuration Area

Description



Main

MainEngine implementation files, that is, the .cpp files:
classify_net_main.cpp/host/classify_net_host.cpp/host/data_recv.cpp/host/util.cpp/device/sample_data.cpp
After the configuration is saved, the CMakeLists.txt file is generated in the build folder under the root directory of the project.
After the compilation is successful, the executable file is generated in the out folder.


Host

Add the engine that needs to run on the host and enter the engine name.
In this sample, this tab does not need to be configured.


Device

Add the engine that needs to run on the device and enter the engine library name ai_engine.
Select the .cpp files:
/device/classify_net_ai_engine.cpp
/device/sample_data.cpp
 NOTE: The .so file needs to be signed to avoid being tampered with. The signing method is as follows:
Call the RSA_generate_key interface of the OpenSSL tool to generate the public key pub.pem and the private key pri.pem. The recommended key length is greater than or equal to 2048 bits.Use the private key to sign the .so file using the SHA256 algorithm to generate the .so.signature file, which is stored in the same directory as the original .so file.Call the SetPublicKeyForSignatureEncryption interface to transfer the public key to HiAI Engine. For details about the APIs, see the HiAI Engine API Reference.






Which of the three tab pages is configured depends on which side the .so file of the engine needs to be used. In this sample, SourceEngine and DestEngine are configured on the  Main tab page while ClassifyNetEngine and TransEngine are configured on the  Device tab page. The following figures show the compilation configuration examples.
Figure  1  Configuration example on the  Main  tab page
Figure  2  Configuration example on the  Device tab page
Click  Build Options  in the  Build Configurations  dialog box. A dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 3.

On the  Main  and  Device  tab pages, set  Include Path  to  /projects/ClassifyNet/inc.

Description

After the configuration is complete, click  Save  to save the project structure configuration. Click  Build  to compile the project structure.
The project structure configuration can be saved in either of the following ways:

In the  Build Options  window, if  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  is selected, the  build  window will display the generation information of CMakeLists.txt files, and the  build  folder that stores the CMakeLists.txt files is automatically generated in the root directory of the project, as shown in  Figure 4.
Figure  4  Project directory example

If  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  in the  Build Options  window is deselected:

If the  build folder does not exist in the root directory of the project or the  build folder in the root directory of the project does not contain the CMakeLists.txt  file, the  build folder containing the  CMakeLists.txt  file is automatically generated, as shown in  Figure 4.
If the  build  folder containing the CMakeLists.txt  file exists in the root directory of the project, the  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt  dialog box is displayed, as shown in  Figure 5.
Figure  5  Automatically regenerate CMakeLists.txt prompt
If you click  OK, the original  CMakeLists.txt file is overwritten.
If you click  Cancel, the  CMakeLists.txt  file in the current project directory is used for compilation, and no more  CMakeLists.txt file is generated.




After the project compilation is complete, the  build  window displays the result, as shown in  Figure 6.

The folders and files that are not selected by the main engine, host engines, and device engines in the project are skipped during compilation.  
If a project that has not been configured is compiled in one-click mode, the  build folder that exists in the root directory of the project is renamed, you need to change the path value directly used to compile the project if the folder contains the  CMakeLists.txt file. Otherwise, the project is compiled using the selected configuration.  
If a project is renamed, you need to change the path value of  Files  on the  Main,  Host, and  Device tab pages. If the previous configuration is run, the generator generates an invalid project with the original project name based on the path value in the original  Files.

project-description-15.html.title: Project Description
project-description-15.html.body:
Project Description
The detection_ssd sample project is compiled based on the SSD detection network. The sample code implements the input of the BGR data to the inference module, and the output of the boxes of the detected targets and the confidence values of the classification.

project-path-16.html.body:
Project Path
The sample path is $HOME/tools/che/ddk/ddk/sample/detection_ssd_asic.
Because the SSD Caffe model is large, it is not included in the product package. To run this sample, you need to download the model file and weight file of the SSD network and convert the network model into a model supported by Ascend 310 by referring to  Data Input.

project-running-27.html.body:
Project Running 

Copy the executable file  sample_dvpp_hlt_ddk  generated after compilation to any path on the device.

 NOTE:The dependent .so files are as follows: lib/device/libc_sec.so, libDvpp_api.so, libDvpp_jpeg_decoder.so, libDvpp_jpeg_encoder.so, libDvpp_png_decoder.so, libDvpp_vpc.so, libOMX_common.so, libOMX_hisi_vdec_core.so, libOMX_hisi_video_decoder.so, libOMX_hisi_video_encoder.so, libOMX_Core.so, libOMX_Core_VENC.so, and  libslog.soBy default, the .so files exist in the  /usr/lib64  directory on the device. You do not need to copy them separately.  


Save the input data file prepared to the directory where the executable file is stored, and run  ./sample_dvpp_hlt_ddk paramList. For details about  paramList, see the "DVPP Executor Tool Instructions" appendix in the  DVPP API Reference.
